{"/service/ndnp/iahi/batch_iahi_kutcher_ver01/data/sn87057934/00415622685/1908020601/0765.xml":{"full_text":"W**IMIL\nypitt\ni\u00ae*1\nIK\nIS#\nIMS\nS'lf.VX.\n22 YEARS OLD.\nClint May passed Saturday night\nin Bed Oak,\nHanr^ *4Wtfr was a buBinesB caller\nin Atlaativ,\n/e'Vday.\nMra. Kerns ^/^uffhter re\nturned from Omaba, y.\nJohn Hanter came in fro_ h\nrie County on business, Tueadb/.\nF. W. Delahoyde of Guthrie Co.\npassed Friday night with relatives\nin this town.\nJacob Carsteus of Audnbon town\nship had buaineBB at the county\n\u2022eat, \"Tuesday.\nMra. Tom Lohner was attending\nto business in Audubon, Tuesday\nand calling on friends.\nProf. K. G. Lancelot, wife aad\nlittle daughter returned to their\nhome at Scranton, Monday.\nI am exclusive agent for the De\nLaval Cream Separator in Exira.\nJ~\u201e\nJOHN NBLSON, Exira la.\nFrank Pfeiffer who is assisting in\ncaring for his father-in-law, John\nBumgartner was an Audubon visi\ntor, Tuesday.\nHenry Reynolds recently residing\nsouth of town was a Monday night\ncaller in Exira, coming from his\npresent home near Caaey.\nJ. C. Powell improved the paBt\nweek in getting bis ice houses\nfilled with ice 10 and 12 inches in\nthickness and clear as crystal.\nMr. and MrB. Matt Doffing of La\ntnoat Mo. who have been visiting\nhis brothers Wm. aud Nick, the\npast week left Tuesday for Carroll\non a visit with her relatives.\nStrong, Bright Eyes and a clear\nl^ead are the results of Dr. Weber's\nBye and Ear treatment and Glasses.\nCall on Wednesday, February 19th,\n/afternoon at Park Hotel. Examina\ntion free. 13\nMiss Ruth Turner of Anita was\nin the city today for a Bhort time\nbetween trains while on her^way^to\nExira where Bhe went to visit her\nbrother, William Turner.\u2014Atlantic\nDaily Democrat.\nLOST:\u2014From my farm in Audu\nbon township last Friday night, 1\nblack sow weight about two hun\ndred and fifty pounds notify\nNICK THIELEN\n4\nRt. 3, Exira.\nThe MieseB Ethel Wheeler and\nGertrude CousinB went to Audubon\nTuesday evening to visit friends\nover night and do some shopping\nin anticapation of the joyful wed\ndings, one of which is new an\nnounced.\nThe Ladies Aid Society of the M.\nE. Church will give one of their\npopular lunches in the League\nroom of their church, Wednesday\nevening Feb. 12 to which everyone\n1B respectfully and courteously in\nvited to attend.\nThe lyceum at the DaniBh ball\nevery Monday night is well atten\nded and is laying the foundation\nfor \"brighter thoughts in our ana\ntomies. Already the oratorical de\nvelopement is quite uoticable while\noccasionally we hear as Shafee\nepere once said: \"I atn no orator\nas Brutus is some orator renowned\"\nMr. Willie Bintner sold his fine\nfarm south of Exira to Dr. Rosen\nbladt of Audubon at $85.00 per acre.\nCome to think about it its not sur\nprising that the doctor prefers in\nvesting in the south part of the\ncounty where the soil is ae good as\nthe best, and in case of a coal fa\nmine, wood can be had at reasona\nble prices its not so everywhere.\nWe understand that Mr. Bintner\nwill not again purchase a farm\nhere but will spend part of the\nsummer looking up a location.\nDanish Lutheran Church\nService in Exira at 10:30 and in\nHamlin at 2-30. Sunday school an\nhoar earlier at both places.\nFOR SALE\nAt the Oak Tree Stock Farm, 10\nhead of Pure bred and high grade\nHereford bulls from 1 to 3 years old\nand 10 head of Pure bredB but not\nrecorded, 3 year oli Hereford cows\nin calf to recorded bulls, also sev\neral good young horses and mules\nbroke and ready for the harness.\nM. I. MASFERSON,\ntf R. F. D. No. 1, Exira\nFOR SALE\nOne Short Horn bull calf one\nyear old. Pedigree furnished.\nNBLS C. JFNSEN\nRt, 2, Exira la.\nMra. Waits is among those on the\nsick liat, this week.\nMr. and Mrs. J. T. Lohner visited\nfriends in Hamlin, last Saturday.\nMiBB Ethel Wheeler returned\nfrom Audubon, Wednesday noon.\nW. P. Turner baa been having a\ntime with rheumatic paina perme\nating hia anatomy.\nQuite a number ot people atten\nded the Oscar Hunt sale Wednes\nday and everything sold well.\nJohn Bonwell of the north part of\nthis county was interviewing the\ndear people of Exira, last Saturday.\nMr. George Guernsey west to\nAudubon Taesday to attend \"East\nLynne\" in the opera house that eve\nning.\nMr. Ralph Hawks moved into the\nFrank Andrews residence Saturday\nit being recently vacated by Agent\nW. B. Fryberger. ,\\,y\nMr. Ed Hensley of Tracyt Minn,\ncame in for a visit with his people\nfor a few days. He will return to\nhis work next week. '-.\u2022\u2022-M-\nClark Griffin's Bale was not very\nwell attended owing to the intense\ncold Saturday but everything brot\ngood prices with the exception of\nthe horses.\nClyde Dimick has been going a\nbout on crutches having received a\nsprained ankle one day last week\nwhen the horse he was riding,\nslipped and fell on its side pinning\nthe young man's foot under itB\nside.\nMrs. M. O. Smith writes to her\nhusband that she is improving un\nder the treatment she is receiving\nand that to effect a permanent cure\nher medical adviser wishes her to\nBtay at least six months where the\nclimate is warmer and not so chan\ngeable.\nThe Epworth League of the M.\nE. Church organied again last Sun\nday evening in the League room of\nthe church and elected a part of\nthe officials as fellows:\nFrank Kreamer, carrier on the\nnew route No. 5 started on his ini\ntial trip last Saturday and was only\nable to get out about 8 miles when\nbe ran into snow drifts on the new\nroad as high as his horses backs\nand was forced to return to town.\nIf people expect their mail deliver\ned at their doors they must make\nsome sacrifices at the expense of\ncomfort and open up the highway\nas well as keep the drifts away\nfrom their mail boxes. Help the\ncarriers all you can for theirB is\nindeed a path not strewn with ro\nses.\nMethodist Church Notes\nThe Sunday School Board elected\nThos. Williams, Supt. of the M. E.\nSunday School for the ensuing\nyear and all other officers were re\nelected. Preaching 11 a. m. and\n7:30 p. m. morning subject \"Dis\ncerning o\u00a3 Spirits.\"\nThe doors of the church will be\nopened for any one who wish to\njoin the church by letter or proba\ntion.\nWanted\n50 head of draft horses, 50 head\nfeeding horses, 50 head southern\nhorses, 50 bead fat plug horses and\nmules all ages and descriptions, at\nExira la. on Feb. 14, 1908. 6\nK. H. STAFFORD,\nThe New Law\nThat must be obeyed. Sec. 436 as\namended rules of the Post Office\nDepartment reads \"No Daily paper\nthat is three months in arrears, or\nweekly paper that is one year in ar\nrears can be Bent through the post\noffice.\" There it is in a nut shell.\nEditors have no discretion,\u2014only\ncomply. Our subscribers will no\ntice that subscriptions Must Be\nPaid if the subscriber wishes to\ntake the Journal (or any other week\nly.) When your paper is one year\nin arrears the post office\nit''\n1\nM. C. Nelson, President\nMiss Delia Hicks, Secretary\nMisB Trola Seibert, piauist\nMiBB Verna Lancelot, asst. pianist\nThe other officers will be elected\nnext Sunday evening at 6:30 p. m.,\ntheir usual hour of meeting.\nISBKS\n-4cutB\nit\nout'' until it is again paid for. Its\nan arbitrary move of the Post Mas\nter General, which will cause mil\nlions of dollars worth of statements\nto be constantly sent through the\nmails making it class legislation.\nThis order will cause bitter hatred\nto the department.\n*i-^V\nBANK SOLD\nis\u00ae\n'Q WAX\nisiifcli\nAtlantic Citizen's Savings Bank Sold\nTo Iowa Trust and Savings Bank\nThe Whitney Bros. Bank of At\nlantic known as the citizen's Sa\nvings Bank, which was bought by\nMr. G. H. Messenger was agaia\nsold yesterday to Senator Jame* E.\nBruce of the Iowa Trust and Sav\nings Bank of Atlantic and the busi\nness will be consolidated by the\nlatter. The Iowa Trust and Savings\nBank thus becomes the strongest\nfinancial establishment in CasB\nCounty. Our former townsman,\nWilliam E. Wissler will preside ov\ner its destinies as cashier of the\nnew concern.\nGeorge Ryner a conductor on the\nBayonne trolley line found a bun\ndle in one of hie eara, last week con\ntaining $3,420. He turned it into a\ncompany's office. Soon an excited\nlady called for lost package, des\ncribed the money, books and pa\npers and handed the conductor one\ndollar for being honest. The con\nductor will now start a bank.\nAd Watterson returned from bis\nvisit in Waterloo, la, well pleased\nwith bis visit.\nJ. B. Connrardy spent Sunday in\nAudubon with bis daughter, Mrs.\nL. E. Simpson.\nGrace West was visiting with rel\natives and friends in Audubon,\nTuesday.\nMrs. Gertrude Petersen com\nmenced working at the John Diai\nick farm, thiB week.\nMr. aad Mrs. Charley Hunt are\nmoving into the first house weat of\nthe Fullerton Lumber yard, this\nweek.\nWalter Nelson is helping Chaun\ncey Gotfredson, south of Elk Morn,\nget ready for his sale, Thursday\nFeb. 6.\nMr. Baumgardner, sluard of the\ncoun'y poor farm arrived in Exira\nlast week to visit his father who is\nquite sick.\nRachel and Norma Doner, who\nmake their home in Audubon with\ntheir uncle Ed Wood, came to Exi\nra Saturiay to visit a few days.\nIf you have Catarrh, rid vourself of\nthis repulsive diseass. Ask Dr. Shoopof\nUacine Wis., to mail you free, a trial\nbox of his Dr. Shoop's Catarrh Remedy.\nA simple, single test will surely tell you\na catarrh truth well worth your kuow-\nWrite today. Don't suffer longer.\nHanien\nSMggigf\nW. J. Lancelot, Editor W. H. Lancelot, Publisher\nKXIKA, IOWA, THURSDAY, FEBRUARY 6, 1908.\n'E are pleased to report to our customers\nthat we have sold out our Rose Comb\nRhode Island Reds fowls. The above\npicture is from a photograph and true to nature.\nThe more you become acquainted with these noble\nfowls the better I'm sure you will like them. Get a\nfew each year and infuse new blood in your flocks,\nthen await results. Thanking you for your gener\nous patronage and wishing you success.\nI MRS. 1 J. LANCELOT, Exira\nMrs. Houston is on tbe sick list,\nthis week.\ntiMVtfgVAri**\nV\u00bb\nCAMPAIGN OFFER\nThe Register Leader. Daily ex\ncept Sunday. Now to July, 1 1908.\nDaily $150. Daily and Sunday $2.25.\nAny new reader can secure the\nDes Moines Daily Regi&ter Lea\nder until after the Iowa primary\nand the Republican National Con\nvention-from now to July 1, 1908\nupon payment of $1.50.\nThe Register Leader prints ALL\nthe news of ALL IOWA and endea\nvors to tell the impartial truth\nabout it. From Wallaces Farmer,\n\"The Register Leader is not only\nthe best newspaper in Iowa but it\nis one of the best in tbe entire west\"\nThe Register Leader brings the\nnews first\u2014it reaches every postof\nfice and is delivered on every rural\nroute in thiB county on the same\nmorning it iB published. Mail your\nremittance now-money order draft\nor personal check. Sample copies\nfree. (This offer is for new rea\nders, only.)\nREGISTER LEADER,\nDes Moines, Iowa\nPlease mention Exira Journal.\nprosperity\n1\nTo show the return of prosperity\nthe town, a National Bank in Cin\ncinnati exhibits a deposit slip for\n$60,162.97 representing remittances\nsent to a local manufacturing con\ncern in three business days. The\nslip was 62 feet long.\nJohn Mertes was an Audubon\ncaller, Monday.\n*',v 'M\nflit\"\ntc\n'V\nh!\nLAND LOTTERY\n150,000 Acres of Irrigated Land Will\nBe Opened To The Public By\nLottery in Wyoming June I\nThe opening of 150,000 acres of ir\nrigable land in Eden Valley, Wyo\nming June 1st 1908, is expected to\ndraw farmers from all sections of\nthe country. There will be comple\nted by that date, an irrigation ditch\nthat cost 1 million dollarB and will\nprovide water enough for thirty\nthousand acres of land.\nTo The Public\nWe are here one week and have\nbeen so busy selling men's Buita\nand overcoats that we have not had\ntime to advertise. We are now go\ning to Bell youth's suits, gloves and\nmittens, caps, sweaters and chil\ndren's underwear at halt price.\nThink of it and come and get what\nyou need. This is no junk as some\npeople would lead you to believe.\nWe have the best clothes in town\nand they cost us nothing, so all we\nget out of onr stock is al] profit.\nCome in before it is gone.\nN. P. CHRISTKNSBN\nThe Honest Real Estate Dealer\nAround the World\nTheirs and Oars\nla Siam all women wear their\nfeair short.\nThere are twenty thousand cliffer\neat kinds of bntterflies\nmmSS\nBrains ean make money\nney can't make brains.\nbut mo-\nIt is better to talk too little about\nmuch thaa too much aboat a little.\nSunstroke killed thirty-two people\nin Melbourne, Australia, on January\n15th.\nJanuary is looked upon by the\nroyal house of Belgium as their un\nlucky month.\nA German physieiaa says only one\nperson in fifteen have both eyes in\ngood conditioa.\nA. German has invented glass tel\negraph poles. The glass is streng\nthened by interlaced wire threads.\nIt is said there are never less than\nforty thousand tramps ia Englard\nand hard tines doablos the nunbev.\nThere are seventea million ehil\ndren ia Russia between the ages of\n6 and 15 who are receiving ao edn\neation.\nEdward Yates, who recently died\nin England leaving a fortune of five\nmillion dollars, began life as a poor\nbriek layer.\n\"Do you believe that mosquitoes\ncarry malaria.\"\n\"Not the mosquitoes around here\nThey eouldn't possibly do it and be\nso healthy.\" ^'\u20225'\nHis alphabet would disagree,\nAlthough some letters well\nknew\nHe never could make C. O. D.\n91.00 PER YEAS\nhe\nKeep up the pace with I. O. U.\n\"I've never had any great Inek,\"\ndeelared the pessimest.\n\"Neither have I,\" admitted the\noptomist.\n\"I made my money by hard work\nand advertising.\"\n\"Hinnisy is a lucky mon. Faith\nan he is thet.\"\n\"Why, how is that?\"\n*'He promised to pay me the five\ndollars he borrowed next week, and,\nhe up and died yesterday.\"\nThe great Sahara desert is to have\na telegraph line reaching from end\nto end of its trackless wastes. It\nwill be protected from the wild Arab\ntribes by military posts at the oases,\nwhich are from 50 to 120 miles a\npart.\nIn Europe green oysters are high\nly prized, and to meet the demand,\noysters are greened by placing them\nas soon as captured in sea water,\nwhere they are kept up for months\nand fed on a species of sea weed,\nwhich imparts the coloring matter to\nthem.\nThe diamonds which the German\nempress wears on great occasions at\ncom-fc are valued at one and a quar\nter million dollars. Most of them\nare hoirloorus of the Prussian crown\nand can only be worn by the reign\ning queen, but she has more than\nhalf a million dollars worth of dia\nmonds that are her private property.\nEmperor Francis Joseph, of Aus\ntria sent a telegram of congratula\ntion on Jan. 30 to Jan Szathmani\nand his wife, Maria who were eele\nbrating the one hundredth anniver\nsary of their wedding. They are\nrespectively 120 and 116 years of\nage. Although almost blind they re\ntain their other faculties. They have\n712 living desaendants. They are\nstill living in the village where they\nwere born.\n\"I've come to give notice, ma'am\nas I'm going to get married.\"\n\"Is that so, Mary? How long\nhave you been engaged?\"\n\"I ain't engaged at all, ma'am.\"\n\"Well, who is the ^appy man?\"\n\"You know the big shop down the\nroad. Well, the shop walker looked\nat me the day before yesterday, and\nyesterday he smiled, and today he\nBaid \"Good Morning,\" aad I expect\ntomorrow he'll propose, and, you Bee,\nma'am, I waat to be ready.\"\nSBS\nAdvertising in the newspapers be\ngan in 1652.\nIn many vineyards of Spain and\nItaly grapes are still trodden witk\nthe bare feet.\nFive tons of human hair are an\nnually shipped toLoBdon, while two\nhundred thousand pounds go to\nParis.\nThe youth who sows wild oats, 'tis\ntrue,\nMust reap as he has sown,\nBut then father oaght to do\nSome threshing of his own.\nJapanese children are net allowed\nto attend school until they are six\nyears old as it is thought to be in\njurious to the health to attend\nschool under that age.\nThere is a factory in Franee that\nis used only for the manufaetuae of\nspiders' thread. It is said that the\nthreap made from the spiders' web\nis lighter and stronger than that\nwhich eomes from the silk worm.\nIt is estimated that almost oae\nthird of the human raee speaks the\nOhinese language. There are one\nthousand words in the Ohinese lan\nguage that have ten different mean\nings. The boys in China are named\ntemporarily uatil their fathers give\nthem a permanent name when they\nare twenty years old.\nJapan's greatest wrestler, Hitachi\nyama will make a tour through Eur\nope and the United States this sea\nson. He will have with him three\nor four other heavy weights, and\nattendants, to give a presentation of\none of the most inseresting, as well\nas ancient, forms of athletics in the\nworld, known as sumo. Tiiis Ja\npanese wrestler is of immense size\nand great strength. He stands five\nfeet ten inches in height and weighs\n306 pounds.\nSoon the delegates will gather from\nthe north, east, Bonth and west,\nThey will pass with flying colors\nand with many a swelling chest,\nThere will be a great commotion,\nwhich will spread through all the\nland,\nEvery moment will be fioisy through\nthe tooting of some hand\nAnd they'll haggle over platforms'1\nand pretend to be concerned,\nJust as though they thought the\npeople never saw and never\nlearned.\nWhen they ask you if you're wearied\nont with living,\nTell 'cm No. \"'-J?\nWhen they ask yoa if there's\" folly'1'\nin forgiving,\n\u2022Tell'em No.\nSay it so they all ean hear\nSpeak it out without a fear\nSpread your gospel far and near\u2014\nTell'em No.\nWhen they ask you if the world i\u00bb\nbound for ruin,\nTell'em No. i'.,\nWhen they ask you if there's trouble\nalways brewing\nTell 'em No.\nAnd the storm begin.\nThe snows xnay pack\nAt the window pane,\nAad tbe skies grow black\nAnd the sun remain\n1\nLaagb whene'er you hear them\ncroak mggt\nGive their sore old ribs a poke\nTreat their growling a joke\u2014\nTell 'em No.\nWinter without\nAnd warmth within:\nTne winds may shout\nHidden away the livelong day\u2014\nBut here in here is the warmth of\nMay.\nSwoop yonr spitefullest up the\nflue,\nWild winds\u2014do!\nWhat in the world do I care for\nyoa?\n0 delightfullest\nWeather of all,\nHowl and squall,\nAnd shake the trees till the last\nleaves tall.\nThen blow, winds, blow!\nAnd rave and shriek,\nAnd snarl and snow,\nTill your breath grows weak\u2014\nWhile herein my room\nI'm as snugly shut\nAs a glad little worm\nIn the heart of a nut.\u2014James\nWhitcomb Biley.\nDeWiti's Carbolized Witch Hazel\nSalve is best for cuts, burns, boils, brui\nses and scratches. It is especially good\nfor piles. Sold by Nick Doffing.\nrX:-\\\n\u2022'\u00abr,\n.\u201e,y\nJ1-\nJ?1'","height":"26344","width":"18675"}}
